defaultIt is the policy
default of most of the Registration and trade bodies to carry out annual assessments of their registered or member enterprises. This usually involves the inspection of one or two installations that have been completed by the enterprise. It is my belief that, in m
defaultost cases, this level of monitoring is adequate and it is difficult to suggest other means by which this may be 
defaulteffectively carried out.
default 
default2.4.0default              defaultthe adequacy of the review of electrical works carried out by Competent Persons;default2.4.1
default              
defaultLessons should be learnt
default here from the “Gas Safe” scheme, whereby it was the enterprise that needed to be registered with no requirement for the individual to demonstrate competence. Experience has shown that, for a large number of companies, on-site assessment or monitoring of e
defaultmployees is just not practical due to commercial pressures and lack of trained assessors. This is still a fundamental flaw with NVQ qualifications and the reason large numbers of “electricians” possess only a technical certificate and not an NVQ, preventin
defaultg them from registering with bodies such as the JIB.
default2.4.2
default              
defaultI believe that a compulsory system of registration via a single body with training and certification provided by competitive suppliers allied to truly “standardized” standards would 
defaultachieve a level
default of confidence in the competence of persons carrying out electrical work.
